{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 10:15:40.565550", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — Clos EBGP fabric\\nContext\\n- Topology: 2 leaves (leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1), 2 spines (spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1), 1 super-spine (super_spine_router_0), 2 hosts (pc_0_0 on leaf_router_0_0, pc_0_1 on leaf_router_0_1).\\n- Addressing: host subnets 10.0.0.0/24 (pc_0_0 via leaf_router_0_0) and 10.0.1.0/24 (pc_0_1 via leaf_router_0_1). Inter-router /31s in 172.16.0.0/16.\\n- BGP: EBGP between leaves↔spines↔super-spine. Observed local AS numbers: super-spine AS 65000, spines ~65100/65101, leaves ~65200/65201.\\n\\nWork performed (inputs used)\\n- End-to-end reachability test (pc_0_0 <-> pc_0_1).\\n- Interface/address and route tables from all hosts and routers (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route).\\n- FRR BGP routing tables (show ip route / BGP table) from each router.\\n\\nExecutive summary / overall health\\n- The fabric is functionally up: pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 can successfully ping each other with no packet loss and low RTT (reachability results showed 0% loss, RTT avg ≈ 2.9–3.6 ms).\\n- BGP is converged and prefixes (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) are visible throughout the control plane (each router\\'s BGP table contains both /24s). Inter-AS path information is present and consistent with the designed EBGP topology.\\n- All router interfaces required by the topology are up and have /31s for inter-router links and /24s for leaves-to-host links.\\n- No evidence of rapid BGP route churn in the snapshots captured (BGP table versions are small and stable; multiple paths are present where expected).\\n\\nDetailed observations (per device)\\n1) pc_0_0\\n- IP: 10.0.0.2/24, default gw 10.0.0.1\\n- Ifconfig/ip shows some packet counters (RX/TX = 2) consistent with the reachability test.\\n- Reachability: ping to 10.0.1.2 succeeded (0% loss).\\n\\n2) pc_0_1\\n- IP: 10.0.1.2/24, default gw 10.0.1.1\\n- Reachability test shows pc_0_1 participated in pings successfully (0% loss).\\n- Note: the snapshot of ifconfig for pc_0_1 shows RX/TX packet counters as 0. This is inconsistent with the reachability log (which shows pc_0_1 sent and received ping packets). See \"Anomalies\" below.\\n\\n3) leaf_router_0_0\\n- Interfaces: eth2=10.0.0.1/24 to pc_0_0, eth0=172.16.0.5/31 to spine_0_0, eth1=172.16.0.9/31 to spine_0_1.\\n- IP routes: 10.0.1.0/24 learned via 172.16.0.4 (spine_0_0) — i.e., leaf_0_0 forwards to spine_0_0 for the other pod.\\n- BGP: local AS 65200, BGP table shows 10.0.0.0/24 as local, 10.0.1.0/24 reachable via spine next-hops; multiple paths available.\\n\\n4) leaf_router_0_1\\n- Interfaces: eth2=10.0.1.1/24 to pc_0_1, eth0=172.16.0.7/31 to spine_0_0, eth1=172.16.0.11/31 to spine_0_1.\\n- IP routes: 10.0.0.0/24 learned via 172.16.0.6 (spine_0_0).\\n- BGP: local AS 65201, BGP table shows 10.0.1.0/24 local and 10.0.0.0/24 learned with correct AS path(s).\\n\\n5) spine_router_0_0\\n- Interfaces present and up: 172.16.0.4/31 to leaf_0_0, 172.16.0.6/31 to leaf_0_1, 172.16.0.1/31 to super_spine.\\n- IP routes show leaf subnets learned via their respective leaf next-hops.\\n- BGP: local AS 65100, sees expected routes to both /24s via leaf ASes.\\n\\n6) spine_router_0_1\\n- Interfaces present and up: 172.16.0.3/31 to super_spine, 172.16.0.8/31 to leaf_0_0, 172.16.0.10/31 to leaf_0_1.\\n- BGP: local AS 65101, sees expected routes to both /24s via leaf ASes.\\n\\n7) super_spine_router_0\\n- Interfaces present and up: 172.16.0.0/31 to spine_0_0, 172.16.0.2/31 to spine_0_1.\\n- BGP (AS 65000): sees both leaf prefixes via both spines (multiple AS-paths), and has chosen a best path for each prefix (expected behavior).\\n\\nAnomalies / irregularities identified\\n1) Interface/packet-counter inconsistency on pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1 eth2\\n- Evidence:\\n  - Reachability test shows pc_0_1 participated in pings: tx=2 rx=2 (0% loss).\\n  - ifconfig snapshot for pc_0_1 shows eth0 RX packets = 0 / TX packets = 0.\\n  - leaf_router_0_1 eth2 (10.0.1.1) shows RX/TX packet counters of 0 in the ifconfig snapshot as well.\\n- Interpretation:\\n  - There is a mismatch between the reachability test output and the captured interface counters for pc_0_1 and its leaf interface. Possible explanations: timing/order of snapshots (counters captured before ping test ran), counters were cleared/reset between samples, or an instrumentation/timing anomaly in how interface statistics were captured. The control-plane and forwarding-plane state (routes + successful pings) indicate traffic did flow, so this is likely an observation/timing artifact rather than a functional forwarding failure.\\n- Localization: the discrepancy is localized to the host pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1\\'s host-facing interface (eth2). No other devices show this counter-zero behavior for the host-facing interface on the other pod (leaf_router_0_0 eth2 shows RX/TX counts consistent with traffic).\\n\\n2) Asymmetric next-hop selection / single-best-path bias (expected behavior, not necessarily a fault)\\n- Evidence:\\n  - Super-spine and spines show multiple AS-paths to leaf prefixes but have selected a single best next-hop for forwarding (e.g., super-spine selects spine_0_0 as best for some prefixes).\\n- Interpretation:\\n  - This is normal EBGP behavior driven by path attribute selection (local preference, AS path length, weight, etc.). It can produce traffic concentration on the chosen spine, but the control plane shows multi-paths available. This is not an error, only an architectural/attribute-driven behavior to be aware of.\\n\\nOther findings (control-plane)\\n- BGP tables:\\n  - Each router\\'s BGP table contains both /24s (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24).\\n  - AS paths shown are consistent with expected eBGP relationships: leaf ASes advertise their local /24s, spines and super-spine reflect those AS paths.\\n  - No obvious route filtering or missing advertisements were observed in the BGP snapshots — prefix visibility is complete across the fabric.\\n\\nLocalization of (suspected) faulty components\\n- No forwarding or routing failures detected; traffic is successfully transported between hosts.\\n- The only localized irregularity is the packet-counter discrepancy on pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1: these two systems/ports are where the counters reported zero while traffic evidence exists. If this were a true fault (rather than timing artifact), it would point to either:\\n  - host-side statistic collection issue (pc_0_1 monitoring/reporting), or\\n  - leaf_router_0_1 interface statistics counters or instrumentation issue.\\n- Note: there is no evidence from routing tables or reachability that leaf_router_0_1 or pc_0_1 are unable to forward/receive traffic.\\n\\nProbable root-cause hypotheses for the observed anomaly (no mitigations recommended here)\\n- Timing/snapshot discrepancy: counters captured before/after the ping test — most likely given reachability success and overall BGP/forwarding correctness.\\n- Local statistic reset or monitoring artifact on pc_0_1 or leaf_router_0_1 (e.g., interface counters cleared, or captured before kernel updated stats).\\n- Less likely: a monitoring or containerization issue that isolates counters from the actual datapath (instrumentation mismatch); forwarding still works.\\n\\nConclusions / overall assessment\\n- The network control plane and forwarding plane are functional: BGP is converged and hosts on different leaves can reach each other with no packet loss.\\n- No routing or reachability faults were identified.\\n- One observable anomaly is an inconsistency between reachability test logs and interface packet counters on pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1 (host-facing interface). This appears to be a local counters/measurement/timing artifact rather than a fabric forwarding failure based on the available data.\\n- No further abnormalities visible in BGP tables, path propagation, interface states, or IP routing tables from the collected snapshots.\\n\\nIf you want, I can:\\n- re-run targeted commands (BGP neighbor summaries, show ip bgp neighbors, or repeated ifconfig/packet counters before/after a controlled ping) to further narrow down the counter inconsistency and confirm whether it is timing/instrumentation or a real interface-statistics problem. (No mitigation actions will be suggested unless you ask.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='daa4e78e-d940-4b2a-bd7d-033316be81c1'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
